==Old English==
===Etymology===
Germanic ''*akraz'', from Indo-European ''*ag̑ros'' ‘field’.

''Germanic cognates:'' Old Frisian [[ekker]], Old Saxon [[akkar]] (Dutch [[akker]]), Old High German [[ackar]] (German [[Acker]]), Old Norse [[akr]] (Swedish [[åker]]), Gothic [[𐌰𐌺𐍂𐍃]].

''Indo-European cognates:'' Greek [[αγρός]], Latin [[ager]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'ækeɹ/

===Noun===
'''æcer''' ''[[Wiktionary Appendix:Old English strong declension|strong]] m''
#a [[field]]
# a measure of land, originally the amount a yoke of oxen could plough in a day; an [[acre]]

